column168: DRIVER WAS REACHING FOR A BOTTLE THAT HAD FALLEN OVER AND ROLLED UNDER HIS FEET INTERFEARING WITH THE VEHICLES CONTROL PETALS.  HE WAS ATTEMPTING TO RETRIEVE THE BOTTLE AND THE TRUCK DRIFTED OFF THE HIGHWAY ONTO THE RIGHT SHOULDER WHERE IN ENCOUNTERED SOFT GROUND WHICH DESTABILIZED THE VEHICLE EVEN MORE CAUSING THE DRIVER TO LOSE CONTROL, THE TRUCK STRUCK A TREE AND ROLLED OVER COMING TO REST ON ITS CURB SIDE. LIQUID LOADING PIPE WAS PARTIALLY DISLODGED DUE TO VEHICLE CRASH AND ROLLOVER OF VEHICLE. LEAKED FOR APPROXIMATELY 4 HOURS THROUGH A SIZE 56 EQUALIZING ORAFACE UNTIL PIPE WAS REPAIRED BY REPLACEMENT OF THE PIPE AND VALVE. FIREFIGHTERS EMPLOYED A FOG SPRAY ON THE LEAK CREATING AN ICE CAP THAT SLOWED THE LEAK AND MINIMIZED THE LOSS AND DANGER. LEAKS ALSO RESULTED FROM DELIVERY EQUIPMENT BEING DAMAGED BY THE ROLLOVER. INLET CASTING ON METER CLUSTER WAS BROKEN CAUSING A DUMPING (DEPRESURIZATION) OF THE SYSTEM WHICH TOOK LESS THAN 5 MINUTES BEFORE IT WAS EMPTY. PRODUCT LOSS FROM DELIVERY EQUIPMENT, APPROXIMATELY 10 LIQUID GALLONS.  PROPANE DISSIPATED IN THE AIR BEFORE FIRE CREWS ARRIVED. ALL PREDUCT RELEASED INTO THE AIR QUICKLY VAPORIZED AND WAS DISSIPATED IN THE MOVING AIR.

During a routine load check, a van trailer containing hazardous waste was found to have a leak at the nose of the trailer.  The driver placed absorbent spill pads on the ground and called his supervisor.  A response crew was summoned from the Cincinnati office.  When they arrived, they donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and entered the trailer.  The leaking drum was located and overpacked in a suitable salvage container.  The trailer floor and exterior trailer side were cleaned with a cleaning compound.  A shovelful of dirt was also scooped up and placed into the salvage drum.  The trailer then continued without further incident to the intended waste disposal facility.  The incident was reported to the Ohio EPA, incident number LHP 120207003737
column169: The drum was found to be defective.  The drum was newly reconditioned and had a crack of about 1/4 inch in length in the side of the drum near the top.  It had not been damaged by any other cargo.  The driver had experienced a full DOT inspection in Illinois earlier in the day without incident.

column168: A spill was detected while offloading a trailer which was transported by SJ Transportation at the Veolia facility in Flanders, NJ.  Upon further investigation, it was identified that there were 22 old 5-gallon poly pails of an antibacterial product (Chem Tron Pro Line DI-750) shipped from the generator to the Veolia facility in Flanders NJ.  It was believed that the pails were non-DOT specification because they were unused product still in the orginal packaging.  The pails were prepared for transportation by stacking them and securing them on a pallet with shrink-wrap.  While in-transit, the pails shifted, cracking the bottom of one pail, which resulted in releasing the contents.  All spilled liquid was contained in the trailer prior to remediation.
column169: All pails must be inspected prior to transportation to determine if they are DOT specification or if they require overpacking into UN specification packaging. Stacking of pails on a pallet should be limited to two high and must be completely secured in a sturdy manner with shrink-wrap.

column168: On February 2, 2012 at 1445 hours, a CSX Police inspection team at the Avon Yard discovered AMOX 13265, a loaded NA 2448, Molten Sulfur tank car to be emitting an odor. The tank car was isolated and the shipper, BP Products North America, Inc. was notified via CHEMTREC, report 20120202-00162, Mr. Gregory Crum, BP Representative, 630-525-0102 was contacted. A CSXT HMS manager responded and found a strong odor and vapor leak at the manway nozzle, and the manway cover gasket between swing bolts 3 + 4. Upon opening the manway, excess product was found on the nozzle lip and gasket face preventing a proper seal. The nozzle lip and the gasket were cleaned off of excess product and the manway cover was re-seated and secured. Mr. Crum was notified of the conditions found and corrective actions taken. AMOX 13265 was released for disposition after inspection found no further odor or vapor release.     HMS Seal applied #1511.  This incident did require a special switch move at Avon Yard.  No AAR 7.1 form is required.      Cause Code: 208  5x(5+1+0)x(2+0)= 60
column169: At 17:20 hours, on February 2, 2012, Mr. Gregory Crum, BP Rep. and CSX HMS Manager, Michael Bethge had a discussion and recommended that personnel loading tank cars using the open manway type loading system, must ensure that the nozzle lip and manway cover gasket are clean surfaces and free of excess product prior to closing and securing the manway cover for transport, this error should have been avoided.

column168: TERRY WRIGHT JUST FILLED AND WEIGHED ANHYDROUS AMMONIA WAGON NUMBER 33, WHICH IS A DOUBLE TANK WAGON, AND WAS PROCEEDING TO PARK THE TANK IN THE STORAGE AREA.  WRIGHT WAS USING A PICKUP TO PULL THE WAGON AROUND THE FACILITY LOT. WHILE PULLING THE WAGON AROUND THE LOT, THE HITCH PIN CONNECTING THE PICKUP TO THE WAGON, CAME OUT. THE HITCH PIN CAME OUT BECAUSE THE SAFETY CLIP WAS NOT PUT INTO THE HITCH PIN.  AFTER COMING UNHOOKED, THE WAGON ROLLED PAST THE PICKUP AND DOWN AN EMBANKMENT. THE WAGON TURNED OVER AND LANDED UPSIDE DOWN IN A DITCH FORMED BY THE EMBANKMENT AND RAILROAD TRACKS. ONE OF THE TANKS WAS DAMAGED ALLOWING ANHYDROUS AMMONIA TO LEAK INTO THE DITCH. ALL APPROPRIATE AUTHORITIES WERE CONTACTED, AS PER REQUIRED ON THE "LIST OF LISTS." WE ALSO CONTACTED THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT. ONCE THE SCENE WAS CLEAR OF APPARENT DANGER THE WAGON WAS REMOVED FROM THE DITCH. THE AREA WAS CLEANED UP. THE CONTAINMENT SOIL WAS REMOVED, LAND APPLIED, AND CLEAN SOIL WAS APPLIED UNDER SUPERVISION OF CSX RAILROAD EMPLOYEES AND INDIANA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT.
column169: A TAILGATE SESSION WILL BE HELD TO DISCUSS PROPER MOVEMENT OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA WAGONS. WE WILL ALSO TALK ABOUT THE PROPER USE OF HITCH PINS, SAFETY CLIPS, AND SAFETY CHAINS WHILE TRANSPORTING ALL IMPLEMENTS. A RETAINING WALL WAS INSTALLED TO PREVENT ANY EQUIPMENT FROM GOING OFF THE EMBANKMENT BECAUSE THE FACILITY LOT IS SLOPING TOWARDS THE RAILROAD AND THE ADJACENT HIGHWAY.

column168: Landstar contacted ERTS to dispatch a contractor for cleanup of an apparent load shift due to a hard braking episode. ERTS dispatched D&H Pump to over pack the leaking container. They then neutralized the spilled material and cleaned up the impacted areas. The contractor disposed of the impacted pallets and the over packed drum was loaded on the trailer to continue the transportation phase to its original destination for use.

A van trailer loaded with multiple shipments of hazardous waste was backed into the dock at the intended waste disposal facility.  A small amount of liquid was noticed on the trailer floor.  A flexbin was noticed to have split down the side.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and began to move the bins.  This caused the damaged bin to split further, leaking approximately 12 ounces of liquid onto the trailer floor.  The contents of the damaged bin were overpacked into a suitable salvage container, along with the cleaning compound used to clean the trailer floor.  The shipment was then unloaded into the plant receiving area.  The Ohio EPA was notified and assigned incident number 1202-31-0398.
column169: The generator was nofified that the flexbin had split and advised they would check their filter press to remove more liquid from the material, and also use more care in loading to insure no contents shift in the bin, causing stress on one side to tear the flexbin.

column168: CCBX 2430 was noted by carrier personnel with product odor in area of car.  Car isolated and shipper notified. column168: A van trailer containing multiple shipments of hazardous waste was being unloaded at the intermediate truck transfer facility.  While unloading the shipment onto the dock, where it would be consolidated with other shipments destined for the intended waste disposal facility, the forklift operator was taking the top pallet of the double stacked pallets off.  The bottom board of the top pallet caught a corner battery of the bottom pallet and pulled it through the shrink wrap, tipping it over onto the trailer floor, causing the fluid to leak out the top.  The battery was righted and a response crew was called.  They donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and used an absorbent material to contain the approximately 12 ounces that had spilled.  The absorbent and spill cleanup material were placed into a suitable salvage container and the battery was replaced on the pallet and resecured.  The LA State Police were called, incident number 12-01024.
column169: The forklift operator was cautioned to use better care when unloading pallets and lift the pallet high enough to clear other objects.

column168: Car was reported to be leaking from the top of the car.  Upon inspection, Mgr. Lerch noted product had leaked down the sides of the car from the "B" end pressure relief valve, however the car was no longer actively leaking.  Further investigation revealed the car was shell full, and the pressure relief valve had activated previously to relieve internal pressure within the car. After determining cause of the release, arrangements were made to reduce the car load.  On 2-2-12 approximately 5460 gallons of product was reduced from the car into vacuum trucks.  Sides of the car were cleaned, and area impacted from the released product was remediated.  Car was secured and released to continue onto destination. Approximately 3 gallons of product was estimated to have leaked from the car.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  During offload, a valve malfunction resulted in the release of approximately 200 gallons of free product.  Product was released to the asphalt surface within the loading dock area of facility.  Atlantic Response, Inc. of New Brunswick, New Jersey was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Atlantic Response, Inc. neutralized the free liquid and used a vacuum truck to recover all free liquid and wash water from the affected surface. column168: A strong chemical /petroleum like odor was reported in the railyard. Loaded tank cars of Isoprene were suspected as being the source of the odor and they were cordoned-off in the railyard. Inspection by contract responders of these railcars revealed tank car UTLX 910417 was the odor source. Intact seal was removed from the valve housing cover. The closure plug on the closed liquid line valve was found emanating a slow product drip. This closure plug was not tool tight and reportedly could be turned by hand. Responders removed the closure plug, cleaned the threaded area, applied Teflon tape to the threads, reinserted the plug and properly tool tightened it. Afterwards, no further product dripping was observed. The small amount of observed spillage was wiped. A de-odorizer was used to mask the product odor that still lingered around the valve housing area. Response was concluded by 2400 hrs. CST, 2/02/2012.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: A BNSF train operating on the UPRR was stopped in a rail siding. A nearby business reported to the local sheriff's department that an entrained railcar was emanating a strong chemical odor. Contract responders were summoned to investigate the odor source. The responders reported finding entrained tank car GATX 61398 as the odor source. A detailed inspection revealed a small amount of commodity had leaked from the fill hole cover. The four securement bolt nuts on the fill hole cover were not tool tight which allowed liquid to seep out from under the unsecured fill hole cover during rail movement. The responders further loosened the fill hole cover securement nuts to relieve internal pressure from within GATX 61398. Afterwards, the fill hole cover was properly secured which ended any further liquid release by 0145 hrs. CST, 2/02/2012. Spillage on the tank shell was neutralized with a citric acid solution and chemical pads were used to wipe the neutralized spillage. No ground impact from spillage was reported. Used PPE and spent pads were containerized in a 55 gallon drum for appropriate future disposal.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  Vehicle rollover on Highway 61 damaged saddle tanks and cargo tank on tank truck.  Both lanes of Highway 61 were shutdown as a result of the accident.  Hankamer Fire Department, Baytown Fire Department Hazmat Team, and Texas DOT responded to assess the site.  Garner Environmental Services, Inc. was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Garner Environmental Services assisted in offload of damaged tanker, and vehicle was recovered from the site.  Site assessment determined approximately 400 gallons of petroleum naphtha were released from a hole in side of tanker, and approximately 300 gallons of diesel fuel were released from the damaged saddle tanks.  Garner Environmental Services utilized a vacuum truck to recover the free liquids, called in utility locates, and scheduled excavation of impacted soils along road shoulder.  Free product was contained to roadside soils and did not migrate or threaten to impact waters of the state.  There were no injuries or exposures reported as a result of the release.

column168: Lykins Transportation, Inc.  Incident Date: 2/8/2012  Incident# 1002480    SUMMARY OF EVENTS: Driver loaded  7,524 gallons of (Dyed Diesel) Fuel for delivery into the facility dyed-diesel above ground storage tank (AST). Upon arrival, driver determined from tank gauge that there was 9" or 486 gallons of product on-hand and as the (AST) capacity is 18,000 gallons (90%= 16,200) that the load of 7,524 gallons would fit.  As delivery requires use of tractor  pump;driver made connections from the trailer compartment(s) to the tractor pump lines to the receiving line of facility dyed diesel tank and initiated the pump-off of the product into the AST.  The dyed diesel receiving line at the bulk facility, that connects to the AST, also shares connection to the top loading mechanism at the load rack.    It was determined that the dyed diesel load arm valve, on the load rack, was left blocked open by one of the facilities tank wagon drivers.   As such, the load arm valve, being left in an open position, allowed fuel to gravity out of the load rack top loading arm and into the dike area of the load rack. The spilled product was contained within the earthen berm I concrete walled dike area contingent  to the load rack.    Initial report  from driver to operations staff was that a spillage of up to 2,100 gallons had occurred,as driver had been unloading a trailer compartment that had 2,100 of product  when he noticed the fuel was spilling out of the load arm at the load rack. Initial reports  were filed with the Kentucky EPA, Kentucky Waste Management and National Response Center indicating a spill of approximately 2,100  gallons had occurred and that it was contained within the earthen/concrete dike area of the facility.  Our localoperations group responded to site and were able to use one of our tank wagon trucks to pump the product out of the dike area. The product  that was pumped out of the dike was transferred into a 1,000 gallon skid tank (AST) at the site. Staff then proceeded to calculate product  spillage and determined that an amount  of 644 gallons was actually spilled- not the 2,100 gallons that was first perceived.  We then re-contacted the Kentucky EPA and NRC and advised that the initial gallons of 2,100 was inaccurate and that the spill was between 600 and 700 gallons (644). The EPA acknowledged the change in gallons. The NRC advised they could not change the gallons from what was previously reported.    Adam Fritsch of the Kentucky Division of Waste Management responded to site and directed the need to have the soil under and around the load rack area as well as clean up of any residuals in or around the concrete wall dike area to be completed that day. We retained the services of Ernest Mc Comas to respond with staff and equipment and excavate and clean up the areas as directed by Mr. Fritsch. Upon completion of these activities, Mr. Fritsch advised the clean-up had been completed to his satisfaction. The soil, absorbents (pads/booms) were
column169: POST INCIDENT REVIEW REFLECTED THAT OUR TRANSPORT DRIVER HAD ARRIVED AT DELIVERY LOCATION, MADE PROPER CALCULATIONS TO DETERMINE THAT THE RECEIVING TANK WOULD ACCEPT THE TENDERED LOAD, MADE PROPER CONNECTIONS TO THE UNLOADING LINES AND INTIATED THE PUMP-OFF DELIVERY PROCESS. THE PRODUCT LINES AT THE FACILITY ARE OF A SHARED NATURE; IN THAT THE SAME LINE CONNECTED TO THE STORAGE TANK ALSO FEEDS THE LOADING RACK AT THE BULK FACILITY. THERE IS A VALVE AT THE BOTTOM OF THE LOAD RACK AREA THAT CONTROLS FLOW TO THE LOADING RACK. TRANSPORT DRIVER WAS UNAWARE THAT THE VALVE TO THE LOADING RACK HAD BEEN LEFT OPEN BY ONE OF THE TANK WAGON DRIVERS THAT WORK OUT OF THE BULK FACILITY. THIS VALVE BEING LEFT IN THE OPEN POSITION ALLOWED PRODUCT TO GRAVITY OUT OF TH ELOAD ARM AT THE LOADING RACK - DURING SAME TIME PRODUCT WAS BEING OFF-LOADED INTO THE STORAGE TANK; RESULTING IN THE PRODUCT SPILLAGE. VALVES WERE DETERMINED TO BE IN PROPER OPERATING CONDITION. VALVE BEING LEFT IN AN OPEN POSITION WAS A HUMAN ERROR.     WE ADDRESSED, WITH THE TRANSPORT DRIVER, THE ISSUE OF FOLLOWING "ALL" PRODUCT LINES AT A FACILITY AND THE NEED TO MAKE SURE THAT ANY VALVES THAT MAY BE PRESENT, SUCH AS IN THIS CASE ON A COMMON LINE, MUST BE IN THE OFF POSITION UNLESS IT IS THE VAVLE LEADING DIRECTLY TO THE RECEIVING TANK. WE HAVE ALSO HAD DISCUSSION WITH THE PERSONNEL AT THE BULK PLANT THAT THEY MUST FOLLOW THEIR PROCEDURES THAT ALL VALVES FROM THE STORAGE TANKS TO THE LOADING RACK AREA MUST BE MAINTAINED IN A CLOSED POSITION EXCEPT DURING THEIR LOADING PROCESS AND THAT ONCE THYE HAVE COMPLETED LOADING THEY MUST TURN THE VALVE LEADING TO THE LOADING RACK BACK TO THE OFF/CLOSED POSITION.    PROPER LOADING AND UNLOADING PROCEDURES ARE INCLUDED IN OUR CLASSROOM AND FIELD TRAINING WITH A DRIVER TRAINER FOR ALL HIRED DRIVER EMPLOYEES. EACH DRIVER RECEIVES A COPY OF OUR IN-DEPTH DRIVER TRAINING MANUEL. WE HAVE ONGOING QUARTERLY SAFETY AND OPERATIONAL MEETINGS WITH ALL OF OUR DRIVER PERONNEL. IN OUR NEXT QUARTERLY MEETING WE WILL INCLUDE SPECIFIC REVIEW OF THIS INCIDENT AND DISCUSS PROPER LOADING AND UNLOADING PROCEDURES AND HOW BEST TO AVOID THIS TYPE OF INCIDENT.

A FRA Hazardous Material Railroad Safety Inspector inspecting railcars in the railyard reported tank car GATX 2887 leaking vapors. Further inspection of GATX 2887 revealed dried product staining at the base of the manway nozzle and the installed manway gasket was protruding out from under the manway cover at one location.  No product was reported impacting the ground. BNSF shipped a replacement manway gasket to a nearby response contractor. On 2/16/2012, the contract responder installed the new manway gasket and re-secured the manway closure. Afterwards, no further commodity vapors were detectable emanating from the sealed manway closure. Intact seal identified as CD-026235 removed from the manway was replaced by tamper proof seal IH-438400. The gasket removed appeared to be distorted, cracked and/or cut.

column42: ENGINES INTERNAL COMBUSTION, OR ENGINES, FUEL CELL, FLAMMABLE LIQUID POWERED
column168: February 1, 2012, the customer made this booking as an non-hazardous cargo with our company.  The cargo was moved by the rail (BNSF) from Elwood, IL BNSF Logistic Park, and arrived  at Los Angeles Global Gateway South - GGS Terminal, CA on  February 10.   Afterwards,  the customer advised our company that the container was contained Hazardous materials (UN3166), then provided a Dangerous goods declaration that was signed on February 3, 2012.  The container was transported on the Rail as an undeclared DG cargo from Elwood, IL BNSF Logistic Park to the GGS terminal in LAX, CA.  Our company rail group confirmed that the trucker could not have provided DG paperwork at the rail.  If a trucker provides hazardous paper work at the BNSF rail for a booking that is showing as non hazardous the BN will automatically hold the shipment up.  They would not have in gated the container if the trucker had advised that they were hazardous.  We were advised that the BN does not require any hazardous paper work from a trucker trying to in gate.   February 14, 2012, we made a change on the booking status from non-hazardous to hazardous in our company's system after received & reviewed a proper DG declaration.  February 22, 2012, the cargo was sailed on a vessel at LAX for Yokohama destined as hazardous on the ocean part.

column168: A FRA Hazardous Material Railroad Safety Inspector inspecting railcars in the railyard reported tank car TILX 190328 with a product sheen on its side shell that emanated from the manway closure. No product was reported impacting the ground. A detailed inspection of TILX 190328 revealed 2 of 6 manway securement bolts were not tool tight. Also, the manway gasket needed replacement. TILX 190328 was carefully moved and placed over the railyard's containment location. The shipper was notified and arranged for RESCAR's mobile repair unit to replace the manway gasket and secure the manway closure. On 2/24/2012, with a new manway gasket procured, RESCAR replaced the defective manway gasket on TILX 190328. Afterwards, the manway closure was secured with all manway securement bolts properly tool tightened.

column169: Shipper/Carrier employees will be informed of this incident and reminded to conduct a proper inspection of equipment before use to help detect potential issues before an incident occurs.  We are going to switch to a stronger material for these fittings going forward.  We have not had this type of failure in the past, but want to do what is possible to avoid future issues.  Finally, we are going to implement a periodic preventative maintenance program on these transfer pumps to help reduce incidents related to wear-and-tear which was likely a factor in this incident.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS HEADING WEST ON HIGHWAY 285 AT A SPEED OF ABOUT 45MPH. THE WEATHER CONDITION WAS EXTREMELY FOGGY. THERE WAS A SMI TRUCK MAKING AN ILLEGAL U-TURN IN THE MIDDLE OF THE ROAD. OUR DRIVER TRIED TO AVOID IT BUT THE BACK OF THE OTHER TRUCK PUNCTURED A HOLE IN THE MIDDLE OF OUR TANKER CAUSING FOR FUEL TO SPILL ON THE ROAD. ALL 5 COMPARTMENTS INSIDE THE TANK COLLIDED CAUSING FOR MORE THAN THE COMPARTMENT CAPACITY OF FUEL TO SPILL ON THE ROAD.    DRIVER CONTACTED US AND CHEMTREK IMMEDIATELY AFTER IMPACT. WE IMMEDIATELY CALLED USECOLOGY FOR CLEN-UP AND KATCO VACUUM TO SUCTION THE FUEL FROM THE TANK TO STOP THE SPILL. BOTH COMPANIES ARRIVED AT THE SAME TIME AT DPS TROOPERS DID, MAYBE ABOUT 2 HOURS AFTER ACCIDENT, DUE TO THE LOCATION OF THE ACCIDENT.    AS SOON AS CLEAN UP CREW DROVE UP, THEY PLACED A BARREL TO STORE FUEL MEANWHILE THE VACUUM TRUCK WAS PREPARING TO SUCTION FUEL OUT OF TANKER.

Tank car NATX 303811 was reported leaking from the top fitting area after its arrival in the railyard. NATX 303811 was carefully moved to and over the facility's containment pit. On 2/21/2012, contract responders inspected NATX 303811 and found the leak source at the valve stem of the closed liquid valve. The valve stem packing retainer nut was very loose allowing product to escape. The responders cleaned the packing seal and properly secured the packing retainer nut. No additional leaks at the liquid valve were observed during a 12 psi internal pressure test. Responders cleaned and wiped non-evaporated product from the top tank shell area, Response was concluded by 1515 hrs. CST, 2/21/2012.

column168: The truck was unloaded around 1130.  The overfilled tank was not identified immediately.  A construction worker reported the overfilled tank about 2 hours after the truck was unloaded.      Fuel tank delivery of fuel oil was pumped in Unit 6 fuel oil storage tank and overfilled the tank.  The storage tank has an high and a high high set point to alarm in the controlroom.   Prior to unloading the fuel tank the station operator verified the tank would hold the quantity based on the control room readings and the set points.  The fuel truck was unloaded by the driver with a Duke operator overseeing the unloading process.  Approximately 2 hours later it was discovered that the fuel tank was overfilled.  A construction craft personnel walked by the fuel tank secondary containment and smelt fuel oil.   They climbed the stairs over the secondary containment wall and noticed fuel oil in the secondary containment.   The control room was notified of the fuel oil in the secondary containment.  Operations and Shaw estimated that the volume was around 850 gallons of fuel that was in the secondary containment around the fuel oil storage tank.   The fuel oil was pumped into totes and moved to a second tank onsite.  The area was cleaned up.      The set points for the high level was 22.0 ft and the high high was 22.5 ft.   The tank overflowed at 21.85 ft.   The alarm setpoints will be lowered to below 21.85 to prevent the storage tank from being overfilled.  The Unit 6 fuel oil storage tank is 136,000 gallons.   One tank truck shipment is 7,500 gallons and increases the tank volume by 1.07 ft.  This was the first time the tank was filled this full.    The secondary containment with diesel fuel was cleaned up by the site.  The carrier did not consider this a DOT Incident.  However, the receiver does and is submitting this DOT Incident report with the information that it has gathered.  While the carrier was on-site, the fuel tank was overfilled due to the receiver's tank settings being set incorrectly.  The overfilled fuel was discovered after the truck had left.
column169: The Duke Energy has corrected their new tank alarm set points to indicate when it is full.  The tank was overfilled due to the alarms being originally incorrect.

Container EMHU 643917 was observed leaking at the Salt Lake City, Intermodal Yard, in Salt Lake City, Utah.  The container was isolated in the yard.. Pacific West Hazardous Material Contractor was contacted and responded to the leaking container. The leak was from two 15 gallon buckets of adhesive a class 3 flammable material.  The cause of the release was improper blocking and bracing.. The buckets were placed in over pack drum and the material was remediated. The container was released to destination.

A FRA Hazardous Material Railroad Safety Inspector inspecting railcars in the railyard reported tank car NATX 300821 with residue product around the threaded connection of the closed bottom operated bottom outlet valve's (BOV) closure cap (BOC). The BOV's operating handle was in the closed position and pinned.  NATX 300821 was carefully moved and isolated on a repair track in the railyard. A response contractor was summoned and inspected NATX 300821 on 2/23/2012. Responders reported that the BOC was easily turned with a 24 inch pipe wrench. As the BOC was loosened to inspect the BOC's interior gasket condition, additional product seeped out at the threaded connection into a containment bucket that was placed under the BOV. The responders stopped loosening the BOC as it was thought that the residue product within NATX 300821 was by-passing the closed BOV. The BOC was tool tightened which stopped any further product release. Visible product leakage around the BOC threaded connection that didn't evaporate was wiped. All other valves and fittings were inspected and found secure. Response was concluded by 1410 hrs. MST, 2/23/2012.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.  The shipper of the residue tank car was notified as to the possibility that the closed bottom outlet valve (BOV) may be allowing liquid to by-pass this closed valve and to have NATX 300821 inspected for BOV integrity.

column168: A HAZMAT PACKAGE FELL OFF THE GRATING (APPROX 3.5 - 4 FT) AT DOOR 4 IN THE UNLOAD.  THE EMPLOYEE WORKING THE IRREG CHUTES NOTICED IT & NOTIFIED HIS SUPERVISOR, DERRICK.  DERRICK IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE DESIGNATED RESPONDERS OF THE LEAKING HAZMAT PACKAGE.  WHEN ARRIVED TO THE AREA, USED DECISION TREE / RESPONSE SHEETS TO ASSESS THE SITUATION.  BECAUSE THE LIQUID WAS CORROSIVE, ALTERED PPE TO INCLUDE THE SILVER SHIELD INNER LINERS.  TESTED THE PH OF THE LIQUID & FOUND IT TO HAVE A PH OF APPROX 1.  I SPRINKLED SODIUM BICARBONATE ON THE AREA TO NEUTRALIZE THE LIQUID, CONTAINERIZED THE PACKAGE TO A LINED SPILL TRAY.  RETESTED THE PH OF THE LIQUID.  ONCE THE LIQUID REACHED A PH BETWEEN 6-9, SOLIDIFIED THE REMAINING LIQUID WITH CLAY-BASED ABSORBANT.  SWEPT UP ALL THE MATERIALS USED IN CLEAN-UP & PUT IT INTO THE LINED SPILL TRAY WITH THE PACKAGE. THEN TOOK THE PACKAGE TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING.  WHEN OPENED THE PACKAGE, FOUND THAT THE SINGLE 1-L GLASS BOTTLE INSIDE WAS BROKEN.

column25: Tesla Miami C/O Dangerous goods at MIA
column168: On February 9, 2012, during the review of export documentation offered for transport. The carrier (Seaboard Marine) noticed on an invoice that container SMLU 783335-1 was carrying non-hazardous as well as hazardous cargo (UN3163 LIQUIFIED GAS N.O.S) The container was immediately placed on HOLD status and the shipper was asked to provide the proper documentation. The same day, upon receipt, review and acceptance of the shipping papers, the container was placarded accordingly and subsequently released for transportation.

The driver left his last stop and failed to completely shut the product valves and left the PTO(power take off)engaged.  Due to the PTo being engaged, pressure built up in the piping and caused the top part of the air eliminator to burst, spilling diesel fuel on the highway.  Duration was for approximately 2 minutes.  Oil absorbant pads, booms, and sand were placed to contain the fuel.  VA DEQ, Roanoke City Office of Environmental Management, and the Roanoke City Police were on hand to direct the clean up and traffic control.  Also on site were ISR Environmental Services and Earth Net.  Product did reach a storm drain.  It was contained, vaccumed out, flushed, and vaccumed out again, to remove any residual product.  Sand was placed on the roadway to absorb the fuel. It was swept up and removed for disposal.
column169: The driver that caused this incident was terminated for breaking policy.  The other drivers were reminded to always make sure all product valves are closed when in transit and never to operate the vehicle when the PTO in engaged.  We are installing air valves on the trucks that will prevent the trucks from moving if the PTO is engaged.

On February 6th at 1615 hours, personnel in the CSXT Curtis Bay yard reported PROX 60175, a loaded tank car of Molten Sulphur, emitting odors from top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Chemtrade Logistics, was notified through their emergency response center.  HEPACO, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the cause of the release was due to deteriorated threads on the liquid line closure cap to the extent that the cap cannot be secured.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to Chemtrades representative.  On February 7th, contractor personnel replaced the defective cap to secure the container.  This incident did not require a special switching move.    Cause Code: 252   NARRI: 5 (5x1x0) x (2x0) =  60

column168: Halliburton tractor hauling an acid transport with 5000 gallons of 28% Hydrochloric Acid  was traveling east on Peanut Ridge Rd in Floyd AR. Halliburton driver turned left onto Coffey/Shiloh Rd. The trailer tracked to the left of tractor causing the rear axle to drop off of roadway. This resulted in the tractor and trailer overturning into the adjacent ditch. Approximately 62 gallons of 28% Hydrochloric Acid leaked into ditch through the manway of the transport. Local Fire Dept and Hazmat Response Crews isolated the incident scene by a 0.5 mile radius, and would not allow for other response personnel to report to the scene for approximately 2 hours until the Hazmat crew evaluated and cleared the scene. After Local authorities released the scene, Halliburton tightened the manway bolts and isolated the leak. Contents from the leak were contained by a land berm in the ditch. Acid was neutralized and remediated by Allied International Emergency.

AT APPROXIMATELY 7 AM LEROY REYES CONTACTED BRUCE WILLIAMS, THE DESIGNATED RESPONDER, THAT THERE WAS A LEAKING HAZMAT PACKAGE ON THE METRO 3 BELT NEAR THE PICK OFF.  THERE WAS A STRONG ODOR THAT WAS IRRITATING TO THE NOSES OF THE EMPLOYEES IN THE IMMEDIATE AREA.  LEROY THEN MOVED HIS EMPLOYEES OFF OF METROS 2 AND 3, AND ALLOWED THEM TO GO OUTSIDE FOR FRESH AIR AS NECESSARY.  BRUCE RESPONDED WITH HIS BASIC PPE, BUT DETERMINED THAT SCBA WAS NECESSARY.  AT APPROXIMATELY 7:05 A.M. THE PRIMARY BELT WAS SHUT DOWN DUE TO METROS 2 AND 3 BEING DOWN.  I DIRECTED PLANT ENGINEERING TO TURN ON THE VENTILATION FANS FOR THE BUILDING AND OPEN ALL DOORS.  BOTH DAN REDDINGTON AND BRUCE WILLIAMS CLEANED UP THE SPILL WITH SCBAS AND TREATED BELT WITH SODIUM BICARBONATE. AT 7:49 AM, I BROUGHT THE PRIMARY BELT BACK ON. column168: Altom driver stated that he delivered the amount of product ordered by customer.  Driver was assisted by a receiving agent who attended the delivery with the driver throughout the unloading process.  When the meter amount had been delivered, the driver cleared his product hoses and the receivers line into the receiving tank.  At this point, the receiving agent went to the tank and discovered the apparent overflow.  The driver and receiving agent determined approx., 10-20 gallons had overflowed into containment.     The receiving tank was approx., 80 feet from the unloading area.  The driver had no visual of the tank because it is located between 2 larger tanks which blocked his view. Past practice at this location was to have 2 receiving agents present during the unloading process. One would stay at the tank and monitor it's level and the second would stay with the driver. This delivery only had one receiver present at the time.  At the conclusion of delivery, the driver blew out the hose lines thus causing the product tank to overflow into containment.  Driver had 40' of delivery hose connected to the receiving line which is 80'. Lines had to be cleared prior to disconnect!
column169: As in past practice, customer needs to have 2 receiving agents on site at all times and should order less product knowing it would be close to capicity eliminating any chance of product loss.

column168: At the completion of line run driver noticed smell when he exited his tractor, he walked around tractor and noticed leakage down trailer side. He immediately made his supervisor aware of the situation. Next step, we pulled the trailer to the back of yard behind shop away from all major drains and away from traffic flow. We then contained the leakage from the trailer by throwing down absorbant and coned off the area to isolate. supervisor placed a recovery drum under trailer to catch leak and absorbent around trailer to contain leakage. A member of the safety team was alerted, he advised us with the next steps to follow. We contacted a local Hazmat recovery team H20 Enviromental to come and clean up spill. When they opened trailer they noticed there was no damage to drum but pallet had busted causing drum to lean forward causing liquid to fall through bung. After containing the spill and positioning the drum back up they tightened the bung and stopped the leakage.

On 02/23/12 at 2003 hrs., CSXT personnel in the Wauhatchie yard, Chattanooga TN, reported that PROX 14122, a loaded tank car of Sulfuric Acid, was leaking from the top of the rail car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Norfalco Sales Inc., was notified, CHEMTREC # 2012-02-23-00229. Marion Environmental, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the liquid eduction line cap  was less than tool tight. Corrective actions were communicated to the shipper rep., Marie Rollin (O) 450 567 2026.  The cap was tightened and the leak stopped.The car was decontaminated and released for transportation to destination. This incident did require a special switch move.     No 7.1 will be required for this incident    Cause Code: 117  NARRI :  5 (3+5+0) X (2+0) = 80
column169: No additional comments.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: On February 26th at 0515 hours, personnel in the CSXT Acca yard in Richmond, VA, discovered UTLX 208863, a loaded tank car of Alcohols, N.O.S. leaking from top of car.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Iroquois Bio Energy was notified via Chemtrec report number 2012-02-26-00004.  HEPACO, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found 3 of 8 manway securement bolts/nuts less than tool tight.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to Iroquois Bio Energy representative, Mark.  Contractor personnel properly tightened the manway securement bolts/nuts with a wrench to secure the package.  The car was then released to destination.  This incident did not require a special switching move.  No 7.1 report required for this incident.    Cause code: 200   NARRI: 5(5+3+0) x (2+0) = 80
column169: Ensure operators are following tank car securement checklist.  Two of eight manway securement bolts/nuts were not applied.  The third securement bolt/nut was less than tool tight.

column62: Misaligned Material, Component, or Device; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: On February 27th at 0519 hours, personnel in the CSXT Bennett yard discovered GATX 53240, a loaded tank car of Waste Flammable Liquids, N.O.S., EPA Waste Manifest No. 004231020 FLE KCS, leaking from top of car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Geocycle was notified via their emergency response number.  HEPACO, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the release was caused by a misaligned manway nozzle gasket. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to Geocycles representative, Don. Contractor personnel replaced the manway gasket and properly tightened the securement bolts/nuts with a wrench.  The rail car was decontaminated and released to destination.  This incident did not require a special switching move.  No 7.1 report required for this release.    Cause code: 208   NARRI: 5(5+3+1) x (2+0) = 90
column169: No additional comments.

column17: UNITED STATES DEPT OF ENERGY RICHLAND OPERATIONS OFFICE
column168: A shipment of 25 kg of solid oxalic acid was received from Capitol Scientific.  The package had 3 sets of orientation arrows but no other external marking indicating the presence of a hazardous material.  A staff member recognized that the orientation arrows might mean a hazardous material was present.  There was no shipping paper but the packing slip (intended for the end customer) identified the material as UN1759 Corrosive Solid NOS (Oxalic Acid), 8, III; we believe this should have been UN3261, Corrosive solid, acidic, organic, nos (Oxalic Acid),8,III. The shipment had arrived to us via ground but had been sent via air through FedEx.  Quantity was not a limited quantity eligable for exceptions under 173.154 because the inner container was >5 kg, and because it was sent by air. There were no leaks, injuries or disruption of service at the receiving location.

column168: An outbound driver reported 20 ft. dry container OOLU 138940 dripping liquid from container's rear doorway and floorboards onto its chassis while in the BNSF's intermodal parking lot. OOLU 138940 previously arrived on a BNSF train and was scheduled for overseas export via a sailing vessel. OOLU 138940 was carefully moved to the facility's containment area. Contract responders inspected the interior of OOLU 138940. All drums were floor loaded and not atop pallets. Responders reported finding two leaking 55 gallon steel drums (UN 1A1/Y1.8/300/11/USA/M5608) with loading or pre-loading damage to these drum's bottom chime area. The damage appeared to be caused by a floor surface nail or screw head protrusion that scraped against and nicked the bottom chimes. Both leaking drums were overpacked, properly labeled and set aside for return to the product manufacturer. The inside and outside of OOLU 138940 were cleaned of all spillage. Afterwards, all intact drums were returned inside OOLU 138940 properly blocked and braced for further transportation.

column168: Truck tractor #605 hauling tank trailer #111 were traveling behind a pickup truck on Highway 97. As tractor #605 approached intersection FM108, the pickup truck had the right signal on, tractor #605 passed the pickup truck attempting to turn left but the pickup truck unexpectedly turned left then tractor #605 attempted an evasive manuever by applying the brakes. the tractor gegan to skid on a wet roadway causing tractor to struck the pickup truck from the rear. The pickup truck came to rest upright in a ditch. The tank trailer disengaged from the fifth wheel. Tractor came to rest upright facing south in the west ditch on FM108. The tank began to roll as it entered the ditch striking a barbed wire fence and utility pole. the tank came to rest on its right side facing east. Texas Highway Patrol and Gonzales Fire Department arrived at the scene. There was an evacuation of about 50 families within 1/2 a mile with duration of approximately 24 hours. There was no injuries, no fatalities and no hazmat release reported. 9 photos are available upon request.

column168: The towing company uprighted and removed the tanker truck from the site.  The cleanup contractor removed the soil impacted with molten sulfur with hand shovels. According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While unloading a small amount of free product leaked from the Air Operated Internal/External Valve.  The release was due to the tanker being over-pressurized.  Approximately one-gallon of free product was released as a result of the incident.  Hazchem Environmental Corporation of Addison, Illinois was dispatched to perform the cleanup and oversee the unloading of the remainder of the product.  Hazchem Environmental wiped down the tanker as needed and placed absorbent pads around the leaking valve to catch the free liquid.  The remainder of the product was unloaded without incident.  Hazchem Environmental Corporation transported one drum of waste to their facility pending disposal coordination.

column168: Tank car UTLX 68272 was reported leaking product from its manway closure during normal switching activities in the railyard. Movement was stopped and a mechanical inspection of UTLX 68272 revealed that the manway gasket was misaligned and hanging out from the manway closure. Contract responders were summoned and reported finding two manway securement bolts were only hand tight. The misaligned manway gasket was cut and required replacement. A new manway gasket was installed and afterwards, all manway securement bolts were properly tool tightened. All other valves and fittings on UTLX 68272 were inspected and found secure. Dried spillage around the manway nozzle base was wiped and no ground impact from spillage was observed. Response was concluded by 1047 hrs. CST, 2/22/2012.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: While preparing to offload product at the customer, the meter discharge valve completely broke off when the driver tried to open to start offloading. column168: A delivery specialist connected hose from 2 compartment trailer to the customer tank for 93% Sulfuric delivery.  He walked back to the trailer and started to operate the air diaphragm pump.  The hose connection was roughly 60' long and when he started the air diaphragm pump, he did not have the tank in line of sight.  He was also pulling Nitric hose from trailer tray simultaneously once he started the pump Sulfuric to prepare for the second delivery at the same customer and during the process, he notice the sulfuric tank started to over flow.  The delivery specialist proceeded to stop the delivery.  The product spilled inside the secondary containment with few splashes outside the tank secondary containment.
column169: Delivery Specialist failed to follow the procedures, where he should have verified the tank level to make sure that there was room in the tank before he started to load product    The delivery specialist & his immediate supervisor talked about making sure that the tank level is verified & if he not sure, to check with customer personnel to make sure there was room in the tank.

column168: A BNSF switch crew reported tank car ASTX 3045 venting during movement in the railyard. Movement was stopped and an immediate inspection by a BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder revealed that the frangible disc in the safety vent had ruptured. The responder replaced the frangible disc in kind. All other valves and fittings were inspected and found secure. Intact seal numbered 524509 was replaced by seal BNSF 174135. Response was concluded by 1300 hrs. CST 2/28/2012. No ground impact from the product release was observed. Afterwards, ASTX 3045 was moved and isolated in the railyard to neutralize product spillage on its exterior.
column169: No additional comments.

column62: Deterioration or Aging; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: A BNSF mechanical carman reported tank car GATX 38 in the railyard leaking product from the top fitting area. GATX 38 was cordoned off in the railyard. After an initial BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder's inspection of GATX 38, it was deemed safe to move and isolated in the railyard. Contract responders were summoned. Responders reported the leak source at the liquid line's threaded closure cap that was not tool tight. The closure cap was tightened, stopping further product release. After GATX 38 was depressurized, the liquid line cap was removed to inspect the cap's interior gasket condition. The responders reported the cap gasket appeared worn/deteriorated. Responders added gasket material within the cap to ensure a good seal after the closure cap was reapplied and tool tightened. Spillage on GATX 38's exterior was neutralized with a soda ash solution. A small area of spillage that impacted the ground was neutralized in place. Response was concluded by 1800 hrs. CST, 2/23/2012.  Intact seal NorFalco 106164 was replaced by seal HMRI 000406.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: JOHN WAS TOLD THERE WAS A LEAKER AND WET PACKAGES AT THE NORTH 8 WAY AROUND 7 AM.  HE DONNED HIS PPE INCLUDING GLOVES, APRON, BOOTS AND GOGGLES AND RESPONDED TO THE SPILL.  WHEN HE GOT THERE HE RETRIEVED THREE PACKAGES: ONE THAT WAS THE LEAKER (SOAP) AND TWO MORE THAT WERE SOILED ON.  HE BROUGHT ALL THREE BACK TO THE CAGE FOR PROCESSING. column168: Part IV. Description:  Container PONU1289228, February 23, 2012    A container was in line to be inspected when an employee noted that it was leaking. The Port Fire Department  was notified and requested to confirm if product or water. They confirmed it was product. Absorbent was placed down and the owner notified. Subsequently, the container was taken to a secure area of the terminal and a containment  system was put around it to capture any additional leakage. The container was opened and found to have poor blocking and bracing materials. Some drums appeared to be slightly off the pallet and were double stacked. All of the contents were removed and checked. Some of the drums appeared to be over filled and had pressurized. The drums were plastic composition. In total four 55-gallon drums in the container leaked resulting in a loss of approximately  118 gallons of product:two drums had minor leaks and two burst losing their entire contents.    At the onset of the incident, a courtesy report was made to the NRC as only  8 gallons appeared to have leaked onto the surrounding  concreted work area. A later assessment determined that 118 gallons had leaked from four drums inside the container but only a fraction of this amount escaped the container. The amount leaked did not meet the RQ in CERCLA nor Title 49. The product did not get into any waterways or storm drains. The leakage was effectively  contained and the container isolated for handling.    As a precaution, the area where the container was first stored was checked for evidence of leakage. It was discovered that the container had leaked and contaminated  four other containers. The area was cleaned by a contractor (M&M Environmental)  and the four affected containers were taken to a secure area for inspection and cleaning.    The remaining intact drums were placed in over packs, markings UN1H2/x300/S/11/USA/M4990 and loaded into two containers, Container MSKU1325310 has 45 drums and PONU7845896 has 29 drums.      Clean up and reloading completed February 24, 2012 at  approximately  8:00 p.m.
column169: THE SHIPPER SHOULD USE GOOD BLOCKING AND BRACING MATERIALS, PROPERLY STOW IN A CONTAINER BY SINGLE TIER, DO NOT OVER FILL DRUMS, AND CONSIDER USING STEEL DRUMS.

column168: WHILE LOADING A UPS TRAILER AT THE UPS WORCHESTER HUB, EMPLOYEES SMELLED A STRONG ODOR FROM A PACKAGE MAKRED AND LABELED AS CONTAINING NITRIC ACID. THE TRAILER WAS EVACUATED, PARTIALLY CLOSED AND MOVED AWAY FROM THE BUILDING, AT WHICH POINT THE TRAILER BEGAN TO EMIT AN ORANGE SMOKE. BOTH THE CONTRACTED OUTSIDE RESPONDER AND THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WERE CALLED.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED AT APPROXIMATELY 14:40 HRS. THE AMOUNT OF SMOKE GENERATED BY THE PACKAGE SUBSIDED AND THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS ABLE TO EXAMINE THE REMNANTS OF THE PACKAGE.  ONCE CONTROL OF THE YARD WAS RETURNED TO UPS, THE FINAL DEBRIS WAS COLLECTED BY THE OUTSIDE RESPONSE CONTRACTOR AND REMOVED FROM UPS PROPERTY FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES AND DAMAGE WAS LIMITED TO A PART OF THE TRAILER.  SUBSEQUENT DATA ANALYSIS LEADS UPS TO SUSPECT THE PACKAGE INVOLVED HAD THE TRACKING NUMBER 1Z073628030327451, AND THE ORIGIN AND DESTINATION ADDRESSES SHOWN ON THIS REPORT.

column168: Crash report indicated that there was no spill and that all cargo was consumed in the fire.  Telephone notification was made to NRC when incident occurred, so I am following up with this report.    Driver was loaded and WB on CR-38 when he departed prepared surface, lost control of vehicle, and struck a utility pole.  As vehicle continued on uncontrolled, it struck a natural gas supply pipe.  Sparks from the electrical wires on the utility pole ignited the natural gas escaping from the gas main starting a fire which involved both tractor and trailer within 5 minutes.  Vehicle was rolled partially over, but driver escaped by kicking out the windshield and egressing tractor cab.  Environmental Management  Services was called (by HAZMAT ONE) to the scene for mitigation and clean-up, various municipal fire departments responded, but fire was too hot to approach the vehicles, and decision was made to let fire burn itself out.  CR-38 was closed in both directions during the event, and Columbia Gas responded and attempted to isolate the gas line, but this took several hours.  Fire crews decided not to attempt to extinguish the fire until the gas main could be secured.  During this time, tractor, trailer and cargo were completely involved in fire, and most of the cargo was incinerated.  Appx 25-30 gallons seeped onto an embankment to a small drainage ditch, but EMS isolated the spill with absorbent socks.  Gas main was eventually secured, fire extinguished, and vehicle carcasses removed.  No waterways were impacted.  Environmental Management Services returned the following two days to excavate, remove and remediate the soil under the crash site.
column169: Driver was 4.5 hours into his DOT day, and adamantly stated that he did not fall asleep.  CR-38 is a relatively narrow road, and driver states that he moved over slightly right to allow an oncoming vehicle a bit more room as they closed. In doing so, tractor tires departed prepared surface, but driver was able to regain control for a few seconds, but when trailer tires went off the road, momentum pulled the entire vehicle into the ditch. I do not believe that fatigue was a factor in this crash.    We have analyzed and reviewed this crash, and have determined that CR-38, while legally able to support class 8 vehicle traffic, and is the most direct route between origin and destination, is not a preferred route of travel for class 8 vehicles. GPS recorded speeds prior to the crash were: 46 and 47 MPH.  We have prohibited our drivers from using this route and stipulated that they use US-224 and OH 53 to and from this destination.  This driver's employment has been terminated.

column62: Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage; Rollover Accident
column168: The driver of the petroleum transport truck (short truck delivery vehicle) was traveling on Virginia Route 10 (15000 block).  The vehicle left the roadway to the right and the driver over corrected causing the load to shift. The vehicle overturned and petroleum product was released from the damage cargo tank, which separated from the vehicle chassis.  Local fire departments responded to the scene.  Released petroleum product impacted the roadway pavement and adjacent unpaved surfaces.  Residual liquids were pumped from the tank, and the vehicle wreckage was removed from the scene.  Environmental assessment and remediation activities commenced shortly after removal of the wreckage. Environmental remediation of impacted soils was completed within one week of the date of the incident.  The release incident was reported via telephone to the National Response Center.  PetroChem was hired as their mediation contractor. Highlands Environmental Solutions, Inc. was retained by the insurance provider to oversee site remediation activities and perform necessary reporting. Petroleum-impacted soil was excavated from the highway shoulder and a field that were impacted by the petroleum release.  Post-excavation confirmation samples were collected from the excavated area for laboratory analysis to confirm the success of remediation efforts.  The excavated area was backfilled, and the ground surface was seeded to prevent erosion.

column168: The driver of the tractor trailer was traveling Southbound on Shady Grove Road. A deer was reportedly in the roadway, and the driver swerved to avoid colliding with the deer. Gasoline was released from the damaged cargo tank (tank trailer) and a fire ensued, further damaging the vehicle and tank trailer.  Due to fire damage, the size and location of initial holes in the tank trailer could not be determined.  The vehicle and tank trailer were essentially destroyed.  Local fire departments responded to the scene and constructed berms to contain the release.  Fire fighting foam was applied to extinguish the fire. Once the fire was extinguished, residual liquids were pumped from the tank trailer, and the vehicle wreckage was removed from the scene.  Environmental assessment and remediation activities commenced immediately.  The release incident was reported via telephone to the National Response Center.  Phillips Recoveries was hired as the remediation contractor.  Highlands Environmental Solutions, Inc. was retained by the insurance provider to oversee site remediation activities and perform necessary reporting.  Petroleum-impacted soil was excavated from the field that was impacted by the petroleum release. Post-excavation confirmation samples were collected from the excavated area for laboratory analysis to confirm the success of remediation efforts. The excavated area was backfilled, and the ground surface was seeded to prevent erosion.  Remediation activities were completed within one week of the date of the incident.

This is an interview of the driver involved in the incident, taken by Lawrence Eastman, Investigator, Fire Check Inc.    INTERVIEW WITH JAMES W. FLEMING    DRIVER OF BOB-TAIL TRUCK THAT EXPLODED    On Monday, February 06, 2012 at 1:30 p.m. I conducted an interview with James W. Fleming at Landmark Service Co-op in Whitewater, WI.  The following information was obtained:    Started working with Cooperative Plus in May 2008 as a Propane Sales & Delivery person.  He was considered a Seasonal Driver.  On Jan 11, 2009 he was promoted to LP Driver and Location Energy Manager.    In Oct of 2011 there was a merger of Cooperative Plus with Landmark Services Co-op.  They are headquartered in Burlington, WI and have offices in E. Troy and Clinton.    On Friday, Feb. 3, 2012 an LP gas incident occurred at approximately 3:10 p.m.  Mr. Fleming had been in the process of filling his Bob-tail truck with LP gas, when a gas leak occurred and a vapor ignition took place.  In short order the relief valve on the tank truck opened and fire went skyward.  This was followed by a BLEVE of the Bob-tail tank.    Mr. Fleming provided the following information regarding his work day on 2/3/12:  • Reported to work at 7:00 a.m. and was the first one there.  • Checked his e-mails and downloaded info to his laptop computer.  • Completed paper work until 8:00 a.m.  • Started to fill his 2006 Kenworth truck, topping it off from almost empty.  • Backed the truck up to a sign and parked.  • Opened the fence gates which were padlocked.  • Opened cabinet and turned on the vapor valve.  • Took cap off the liquid line and put liquid line on truck and tightened with a spanner wrench, then opened both valves on hose and truck.  He then went back and got vapor line and hooked it up with a pipe wrench and opened the valves on it.  • Pulled up the emergency levers.  • Turned the pump on with on/off swithch  • Cherked the pressure on the tank and opened properly.  • Normal fill time is approx 40 to 45 minutes.  • Shut off the pump   • Flipped down the emergency valves and turned off the valves.  • Relieved the pressure on the liquid line for approx a minute.  • Opened the hose and dumped liquid on the ground.  • Completed the vapor line first.  • Now ready for delivery of auto fills and call-ins.    Returned back to yard at noon for a second load of LP.  Refilled Bob-tail and went back out on more deliveries.    At approx. 2:30 p.m. he returned back to the yard and started to fill, or top off his truck for Sat. morning run.  The incident happened at approx 3:10 p.m.   • The truck was shut off while he went into the office to talk with the IT man  • He was done filling his truck by 3:00 p.m.  • The vapor line was disconnected and hanging up.  • The liquid line was still connected while he was getting the spanner wrench.  • He was at the rear of his truck with his back to the bulk tank when he heard a lowed clap sound.  It was very distinguishable.  Then he heard a metallic sound hitting someth

column168: AN EMPLOYEE OF SKYLAND GRAIN, LLC. WAS PULLING TWO ANHYDROUS AMMONIA TRAILERS TO A FARMER'S FIELD, LOCATED 5 MILES SOUTH AND 2 1/2 MILES WEST OF THE CITY OF WALSH, CO. HE WAS PARTWAY THROUGH THE TOWN WHEN HE HIT A BUMP, HEARD A LOUD BANG, AND SAW A WHITE CLOUD OF VAPOR FROM BEHIND HIM. HE IDENTIFIED A DANGER AND CONTINUED TO DRIVE UNTIL HE REACHED A SAFE DISTANCE.  THERE HE NOTIFIED THE WALSH FIRE DEPT. AFTER THAT, HE BEGAN GOING FROM HOUSE TO HOUSE TO GET THE RESIDENTS AWAY FROM THE TRAILER. THE WALSH FIRE DEPT. ARRIVED AND BEGAN PUTTING WATER ON THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER. ANHYDROUS AMMONIA HAS A STRONG AFFINITY FOR WATER AND READILY BINDS WITH IT.    WITH CONTINUING WATER KNOCKING DOWN THE ANHYDROUS CLOUD, EVERYONE STAYED UNTIL COLORADO STATE PATROL HAZARDOUS MATERIALS UNIT OFFICER TERRY CLODFELTER ARRIVED. IT WAS DECIDED TO PUT A WOODEN PLUG IN THE HOLE IN THE TANK TO FACILITATE THE TANKS REMOVAL. THIS WAS SUCCESSFULLY DONE AND THE TANK WAS TAKEN TO A SAFE LOCATION.
column169: TRAINING WAS EVIDENT IN THE RAPID CONTROL OF THE INCIDENT SITE.

column42: GASOHOL GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 6:02 AM, A TRUCK OWNED AND OPERATED BY GOODMAN TANK LINES, INC. ROLLED OVER WHILE MAKING A TURN ONTO THE RAMP FROM SKYTOP MOUNTAIN ROAD TO I-99 (SOUTHBOUND) AT GRAYS WOODS. THE ACCIDENT RESULTED IN A RELEASE OF THE CONTENTS OF THE TANK (8,500 GALLONS OF GASOLINE, 500 GALS WAS PREMIUM) WHICH PROMPTLY IGNITED. THE DRIVER WAS ABLE TO ESCAPE UNDER HIS OWN POWER. THE COUNTY CONTACTED EAGLE TOWING AND RECOVERY TO HELP WITH THE INCIDENT AND THEY WERE LATER OFFICIALLY HIRED BY THE RP TO COMPLETE THE CLEANUP. WHEN I ARRIVED AT APPROXIMATELY 7:15 AM, THE MAJORITY OF THE GASOLINE ON THE SURFACE OF THE GROUND BURNED AWAY AND LITTLE WAS LEFT OF THE VEHICLE. DURING MY INITIAL WALK AROUND THE SITE IT DID NOT APPEAR THAT ANY FUEL FLOWED OVER THE SURFACE TO THE CATCH BASIN AT THE LOWER END OF THE MEDIAN. AT THAT TIME ALPHA FD HAD NOT YET EXTINGUISHED THE FLAMES. BEFORE THEY APPLIED THE FOAM, WE DECIDED TO DIG AND INTERCEPTOR TRENCH IN THE SWALE TO PREVENT ANY RUNOFF FROM FLOWING TO THE DRAIN. THE FLAMES WERE EXTINGUISHED AND EXCAVATION OF THE CONTAMINED SOIL BEGAN. I DISCUSSED THE WORK WITH CHRIS MANY AND EAN JOSEPHSON OF PENNDOT. THEY SAID THAT THE MEDIAN DOES NOT HAVE A GEO-SYNTHETIC CLAY LINER BUT ALL DITCHES ARE LINED. DENNIS WOLFE LATER ARRIVED AND WE USED PIDS TO HELP DETERMINE WHERE THE CONTAMINATION WAS CONCENTRATED AND THE EXTENT OF THE EXCAVATION REQUIRED. EAGLE ALSO SUBCONTRACTED MOUNTAIN RESEARCH TO USE A HYDRAULIC GEO-PROBE TO TAKE CORE SAMPLES (5) AROUND THE PERIMETER OF THE SPILL. THE MEDIAN CONSISTED OF 6-12 INCHES OF SOIL OVER FRACTURED LIMESTONE ROCK, SOME OF WHICH WAS >3 FEET IN DIAMETER. THE GASOLINE FLOWED THROUGH THE SOIL INTO THE LARGE VOIDS BETWEEN THESE ROCKS. THERE APPEARED TO BE A SINKHOLE IN THE SWALE WHICH MAY HAVE ALLOWED EASIER ASSCESSES TO THIS LAYER. EAGLE EXCAVATED UP TO 8 FEET AND WAS UNABLE TO FIND THE BOTTOM OF THE CONTAMINATION. WE DETERMINED THAT THE BEST COURSE OF ACTION FOR TODAY WAS TO REMOVE THE UPPER SOIL TO EXPOSE THE LARGE ROCKS AND ENCOURAGE VOLATILIZATION OF THE GASOLINE. THE PIT WILL BE OPEN THROUGH THE WEEKEND (PROTECTED BY ORANGE CONSTRUCTION FENCING) AND WILL LIKELY BE BACKFILLED NEXT WEEK.  THE LIMITS OF THE EXCAVATION APPEARS TO BE LIMITED TO THE MEDIAN. THROUGHOOUT THE DAY, I CHECKED THE CLOSEST WATERWAY (UNT TO BUFFALO RUN) BUT DID NOT SEE ANY INDICATION THAT THE FUEL TRAVELED THAT FAR.  AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE, I INSTALLED A BOOM DOWNSTREAM OF THE ACCIDENT TO CAPTURE ANY FUEL THAT MAY LEACH OUT OF THE GROUND. DENNIS WOLFE WILL BE THE PRIMARY CONTACT FOR THE REMEDIATION OF THE SITE. SHERYL SINCLAIR AND JESSICA RITENOUR (DEP GEOLOGISTS) WERE ALSO ONSITE INVESTIGATING THE ACCIDENT.    METER READINGS: PID>2,000 PPM IN THE TRENCH.  02,LEL; RAD; PID
